{
  "texts": [
    "Since this holds for each i ∈ I, we have e ≤ b ∧ i∈I ■ 1 a i and f ≤ a ∧ i∈I ■ 2 b i, which with (7.1) implies ⟨e, f, g⟩ ≤ ⊟⟨a, b, c⟩.Case 2: c = ∅.",
    "Then by the definition of ⊟, b, and the complete multiplicativity of ■ 2, we have: there is some i ∈ I for which c i = ∅ and hence ⟨e, f, g⟩ ≤ ⟨0, a ∧ ■ 2 b i, {1}⟩.",
    "Thus, e ≤ 0, and for each i ∈ I, f ≤ a ∧ ■ 2 b i, whence f ≤ a ∧ i∈I ■ 2 b i.",
    "It follows by (7.2) that ⟨e, f, g⟩ ≤ ⊟⟨a, b, c⟩.",
    "This completes the proof that ⊟⟨a, b, c⟩ is the greatest lower bound."
  ]
}